Foot-and-mouth disease [FMD] - Mauritius
----------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 17 Aug 2016 from Dr Deodass Meenowa, Principal Agricultural Officer (Veterinary Services), Division of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agro-Industry and Food Security, Reduit, Mauritius

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of start of the event: 7 Jul 2016
Date of confirmation of the event: 13 Aug 2016
Reason for notification: 1st occurrence of a listed disease in the country
Causal agent: Foot and mouth disease virus [FMDV]
Serotype: O
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (basic)
This event pertains a defined zone within the country.

New outbreaks (159)
Outbreak cluster 1: Rodrigues, Mauritius (158 outbreaks)
Date of start of the outbreak: 7 Jul 2016
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / - / - / - / 488 / 0
Sheep/goats / - / - / - / 1068 / 0
Swine / - / - / - / 190 / 0
Affected population: up to 14 Aug 2016, 158 farms have been affected.

Outbreak 2: Vallée des Prêtres, Port-Louis, Mauritius
Date of start of the outbreak: 1 Aug 2016
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: village
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 41 / 5 / 2 / 39 / 0
Goats / 12 / 0 / 0 / 12 / 0
Sheep / 48 / 0 / 0 / 48 / 0
Affected population: 6 cattle were imported into Mauritius from Rodrigues, a dependency of Mauritius, situated at 350 miles [563 km] on the North-East coast of Mauritius on 15 Jul 2016. They were introduced into the local herd including sheep and goats. They showed 1st signs 14 days after introduction into this herd. This infection spread to neighbouring farms and affected local herds.

Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle / 41 / 5** / 2 / 527 / 0
Sheep/goats / - / ** / - / 1068 / 0
Swine / - / ** / - / 190 / 0
Goats / 12 / 0 / 0 / 12 / 0
Sheep / 48 / 0 / 0 / 48 / 0
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Cattle / ** / ** / ** / **
Sheep/goats / ** / ** / ** / **
Swine / ** / ** / ** / **
Goats / 0 / 0 / - / 100
Sheep / 0 / 0 / - / 100
* Removed from the susceptible population
** Not calculated because of missing information

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: introduction of new live animals; legal movement of animals; fomites (humans, vehicles, feed, etc); airborne spread.

Epidemiological comments: 1st case in Rodrigues was on 7 Jul 2016 and treated as an isolated case. Since there was a continuous increase in the number of cases, blood samples were collected and analysed at the Animal Health Laboratory at Reduit, in Mauritius. 1st positive FMD diagnosis was done by competitive ELISA. Another positive diagnosis from cattle in Mauritius was on 5 Aug 2016 by competitive ELISA. Confirmation from Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (OVI) in South Africa is awaited. The French Food Security Agency (ANSES) has confirmed FMD virus by PCR and virus isolation; serotype O has been confirmed by antigen detection ELISA on viral isolate.

Control measures
Measures applied: movement control inside the country, disinfection/disinfestations, traceability, quarantine, surveillance outside containment and/or protection zone; stamping out; official destruction of animals products; official disposal of carcasses, by-products and waste; surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; zoning; vaccination permitted (if a vaccine exists), no treatment of affected animals
Measures to be applied: vaccination in response to the outbreak(s)

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type/ Species / Test / Test date / Result
French Food Security Agency (ANSES), France (OIE reference laboratory) / Cattle / antigen (Ag) detection ELISA / 13 Aug 2016 / Positive
Onderstepoort Veterinary Institute (OVI), South Africa (OIE Reference Laboratory) / Cattle / virus isolation / - / Pending

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

[The location of these outbreaks can be seen on the interactive map included in the OIE report at the source URL above.]

